ay back to the Fordist family wage for which it longs. In fact, Szalay argues, black-market melodramas lament the very economic transformations that untethered TV viewing from the daily rhythms of the nine-to-five job and led, ultimately, to prestige TV.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aFiction television programszUnited StatesxHistory and criticism. 0aTelevision programszUnited StatesxHistoryy21st century. 0aTelevision serieszUnited StatesxHistory and criticism. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / General.2bisacsh  aquality TV, prestige TV, black-market melodrama, deindustrialization, allegory, white middle class, family wage, separate spheres.40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226824796423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226824796/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles